Fairness Evaluation of Clustering Models

Jonathan Li, David Qiu

Fall 2022

1 Project Information

This project was performed in Fall 2022 as part of the Data Analytics and Research class at RPI. The purpose of the class was to give students an opportunity to learn and participate in ongoing research in data analytics at Rensselaer, and this project in particular was performed in tandem with research on the Fairness Metrics Ontology for Clustering. The students got a chance to learn about ontologies, contribute to the fairness metrics ontology for clustering, and demonstrate usage of the fairness metrics ontology. In particular, this document describes the implementation of fair clustering algorithms and metrics, and the analytical results of an evaluation of these models.

2 Abstract

With the growing applications of machine learning in the whole gamut of industries, companies have found themselves plagued with questions and complaints about the results produced by these machine learning models. One particular issue these effective models face is the issue of fairness - whether or not the results produced by these models are fair and reliable. This is especially a problem in methods like classification and clustering - our main focus - that group similar individuals together which creates a sense of discrimination. For many companies, fairness is not the concern and instead a hindrance towards their purpose - the pursuit of monetary gains. Others, however, acknowledge fairness as a concern to be considered and have conducted their own studies on evaluating fairness and mitigating bias in machine learning, developing concepts that are deemed fairness notions, fairness metrics, and mitigation methods. Prior research has developed various fairness notions (concepts that are used to classify fairness), fairness metrics (a calculated value to determine how fair the model is based on a fairness notion), and mitigation methods (algorithms to apply in order to improve clustering fairness). Some of these are derivations of others, while others evaluate essentially the same concept in different ways. Nevertheless, we have observed an abundance of these notions, metrics, and mitigation methods, but a severe lack of information regarding applying these concepts, especially in the problem of clustering. Hence, we compiled information on these concepts of clustering fairness and their intricacies to be used in the creation of an ontology for fairness in clustering- a guide for others who seek to incorporate fairness in their machine learning pursuits.

3 Introduction and Background

Fairness is a concern that has recently been emerging in the field of machine learning, introducing an important issue of whether or not machine learning methods are providing fair results. While this may not be important for for-profit companies and start ups, it is an essential consideration for any other institution that uses machine learning for any task as it is crucial that human biased decision making is not reinforced in the model as to prevent discrimination.

Correspondingly, many researchers and professionals to develop their own notion of fairness for various kinds of machine learning: regression, classification, and even clustering. Some notions come with relevant metrics and mitigation methods by which these notions are evaluated while many others do not, but the introduction of all of these new fairness notions have introduced an issue that we aim to solve: organizing and classifying the assortment of new fairness notions, metrics, and mitigation methods.

Our team has taken on the task of gathering and clarifying information with regards to fairness in clustering, specifically, our goal is to find all existing notions of fairness in clustering, their respective evaluation metrics, and their respective mitigation methods. The approach the clustering team has taken is to do a broad search for existing methods, beginning our search at a review paper on clustering fairness and branching out into deeper dives on each introduced method in the paper, along with finding notions that are also not contained within the paper.

With this collected information at hand, we seek to obtain a deeper understanding of the intricacies of the relationships between these fairness notions. As such, we have also evaluated the use cases for these fairness notions, the limitations, any compatibility/incompatibility, addressed biases, and any methods to mitigate unfairness evaluated by these notions and metrics. The final steps in our process is to evaluate these notions, metrics, and methods on a respectable dataset with protected classes to evaluate the effectiveness of these introduced metrics. We intend to hand off this information to be used in the creation of an ontology that will be utilized to help laymen in judging the fairness of clustering to determine which notions and methods are best in a given scenario.

4 Our Approach

The information detailed in this paper was obtained in the following manner: we initially begun by doing a literature search on papers we found regarding fairness and mitigation in clustering on Google scholar. We ordered the compiled papers by the number of references and an estimated priority value on the relevance, importance, and density of the information in each paper. With this information, our first step was to read the overview paper produced by IEEE to gain a breadth of knowledge on the various clustering fairness methods that have been introduced so far. For each concept, we read the paper in which the concept was introduced and the papers that apply the concept. We compiled this information into a spreadsheet detailing the use cases, compatibility, limitations, formulation, notion, metric, and mitigation method of each concept. We then branched out to the other papers we found, noting any identical notions under different names and any mitigation methods that are algorithm agnostic. We supplemented the spreadsheet with this information, producing the final spreadsheet to be used for the ontology.

5 Problems Tackled

As previously stated, our main goal is to provide clarity to laymen trying to incorporate fairness into their machine learning architecture, particularly for clustering by gathering and building a knowledge base containing information about fairness notions, their derivatives, the use cases, limitations, co-compatibility, metrics, and mitigation methods. Hence, some of the main questions we aimed to address were: “What is a notion?”, “What is a metric?”, “How do we differentiate between a notion and a metric?”, “Are there any umbrellas that these notions fall under?”, “Which notions are algorithm specific, and if so, which algorithm?”, “When should we use metric x and when can we use it?”, and “What is the significance behind this notion; why address it?”.

6 Clustering Algorithms

There are six main algorithms for clustering that we will consider fairness in during our research. They are: Center-Based, Hierarchical, Mixture-Model-Based, Graph-Based, Fuzzy, and Combinatorial Search-Based. Of these, we have only found notions for Center-Based and Hierarchical Clustering though a large set of notions we have found are algorithm agnostic, meaning they can be applied to any of the other seven clustering algorithms. Below is a short description detailing each clustering algorithm and its subsets.

6.0.0.1 Center-Based

Center-based clustering is clustering whose objective is to assign points such that every point is more similar to its center than any other cluster center. The center of each cluster is a centroid, being either the average of all points in the cluster or a medroid, the most representative point in a cluster. The various forms of Center-Based clustering are: K-Means, K-Medoids, ISO-Data, and K-Center Clustering, each with their own, slightly different objective function.

6.0.0.2 Hierarchical

There are two approaches to hiearchical clustering, being agglomerative and divisive. Agglomerative is a bottom up approach where each datapoint is treated as a cluster and merged with other clusters until a few are left. Divisive is the opposite, being a top down approach. The variations of Agglomerative Clustering include: CURE (Clustering using Representatives), Ward’s Method, BIRCH (Balanced Iterative Reducing and Clustering using Hierarchies), and ROCK (Robust Clustering using Links). The variations of Divisive Clustering include: DIANA (Divisive Analysis) and MONA (Monothetic Analysis).

6.0.0.3 Mixture-Model Based

Mixture-Model Clustering is a probabilistic model for representing the presence of subpopulations using the expectation-maximization optimization iterative process.There are three main variations of this, being GMM-EM (Gaussian Mixture Model based Expectation Maximization), EMMIX (Expectation Maximization-based Mixture program), and Autoclass.

6.0.0.4 Graph-Based

In Graph-Based clustering, objects are represented as nodes and there are weights between two nodes, which represent the distance between the two nodes. From this, there are many ways to obtain clusters from a graph, one of which being a minimal spanning tree. The two main variations are CLICK (Clustering Identification via Identity Kernels) and DTG (Delaunay Triangulation Graph Based Clustering).

6.0.0.5 Fuzzy (Soft)

Fuzzy, or Soft, clustering is a clustering algorithm where each point can be a member of more than one cluster.Two of the most common Fuzzy clustering algorithms are FCM (Fuzzy C-Means) and Hiearchical Unsupervised Fuzzy Clustering.

6.0.0.6 Combinatorial Search-Based

Combinatorial Clustering is a clustering method using a combinatorial optimization problem where clustering is performed by minimizing an objective function under a constraint. This is a very common algoritm used when developing mitigation methods due to its flexibility with constraints. The two most common variants are GGA (Genetically Guided Algorithm), and GKA (Genetic K-Means Algorithm).

7 Fairness Notions/Metrics

The following section details the fairness notions we have found during our literature search, their respective metrics, and their overarching fairness notions.

7.0.1 Disparate Impact

Disparate impact measures the proportion of individuals from one protected group that receive one outcome to those of another group that receive the same outcome. It is ideal for them to be equal.

7.0.1.1 Balance

The closer the ratio of two classes are to being equal, the more balanced the cluster, maxing out at balance = 1 where the classes are equally represented.

7.0.1.2 Bounded Representation

A cluster is fair if, for all protected classes, the proportion of members of those classes are within a defined bound and at most 0.5(preventing dominance).

7.0.1.3 Max Fairness Cost

A clustering is fair if each group’s proportion in each cluster is close to their respectively defined ideal proportion.

7.0.1.4 Essential Fairness

A cluster is essentially fair if there exists a fractional fair cluster where for each color h, the number of color h points in C differ by at most 1 from the mass of color h points in C’.

7.0.2 Independence (Statistical Parity)

Independence is satisified when the distribution of outcome for all groups is the same. This means that the outcome should not be dependent on the group, or protected attribute in this case.

7.0.2.1 Entropy

A fair deep clustering is group invariant and maximizes entropy, meaning it does not consider sensitive/protected attributes.

7.0.2.2 Abraham et al Group Fairness

A fair clustering preserves proportional representation of protected classes within clusters as its representation in the whole dataset.

7.0.2.3 Group Egalitarian, Leximin, and Utilitarian

A fair clustering maximizes equality of representation subject to an upper bound and lower bound on the clustering constraint. A proportional violation is the largest deviation from the bounds. Minimize all proportional violations starting from the largest.

Group Leximin minimizes the sum of proportional violations for each class and Group Egalitarian minimizes the largest proportional violation across all protected classes.

7.0.3 Individual Fairness

Individual Fairness states that similar individuals should be treated the same. This means that two users who have the same height, weight, and age should be given the same assignment.

7.0.3.1 Kleindessner et al Individual Fairness

A data point is individually fair if the average distance from it to the other points in its cluster is not greater than the average distance from it to points in other clusters.

7.0.3.2 Distributional Individual Fairness

A clustering is fair if the statistical distance of the f-divergence of the distribution of each pair of samples is smaller than the distance using the F metric that measures fairness between pairs of points.

7.0.3.3 Per-Point Fairness

Every point j has a set of points S that it percieves as similar to itself. A fair clustering will give point j an alpha close treatment as those in S. A clustering is fair if the quality of service j recieves(distance from center) is at most a times the best quality in S.

7.0.3.4 Aggregate Fairness

Every point j has a set of points S that it percieves as similar to itself. A fair clustering will give point j an alpha close treatment as those in S. A clustering is fair if the quality of service j recieves(distance from center) is at most a times the average quality in S.

7.0.4 Novel Notions

These are notions that do not lie under any general notion’s umbrella.

7.0.4.1 Jung et al Indivudal Fairness

A clustering is fair if each center serves approximately the same number of data points and the center for each data point is no farther than the n/kth farthest other data point.

7.0.4.2 Social Fairness Cost

A clustering is socially fair if it minimizes the maximum of the k-means objective applied to each protected group.

7.0.4.3 Proportionality

Any n/k points are entitled to form their own cluster if there is a another center closer in distance for all n/k points.

7.0.4.4 Diversity Aware Fairness

A diversity aware fair clustering should contain at least a center from every group.

7.0.4.5 Fair Summaries

A clustering is fair if the protected group are equally represented in the summary (set of centroids).

7.0.4.6 Alpha-Pairwise Fairness

A clustering is Alpha pairwise Fair if every pair of points has a probability of at least alpha of being assigned to different centers where alpha is a function of distance between the points.

7.0.4.7 Beta-Community Preserving Fairness

A clustering is Beta community preserving if every community has a probability of at most beta of being split into more than t clusters where beta is an increasing function of diameter D and a decreasng function of clusters t. A community is a subset of points with diameter D and does not need to be known or identified.

9 Mitigation Methods

The following section details the various bias mitigation methods that we found in our literature search.

8.0.0.1 Fairlet Decomposition

Fairlet Decomposition is a mitigation method that involves finding fairlets, or minimal sets that satisfy fair representation, and then conduct clustering on the fairlets to obtain a fair clustering. It is commonly used in Center-Based Clustering to mitigate Balance.

8.0.0.2 Fairlet Decomposition Constrained Spectral Clustering

This method uses the concept behind fairlet decomposition - equal representation or balance - as a constraint in spectral clustering to form fair clusters.

8.0.0.3 General Variational Framework for Fair Clustering

This method introduces an original Kullback-Leibler fairness loss term to be used in the objective function of a large array of clustering algorithms from combinatorial to spectral clustering.

8.0.0.4 Fair-Lloyd

This method is a slight modification of the normal k-mean method with the goal of making the objective and outcome more equitable to subgroups. Fair k-means minimizes the higher average cost and uses line search as a minimization procedure to assing clusters fairly. This is a modification of Lloyd’s heuristic for k-means which is termed Fair-Lloyd.

8.0.0.5 Fair K-Means (FairKM)

The FairKM algorithm attempts to preserve proportional representation of protected classes in clusters by incorporating a novel fairness loss term called deviation in the k-means objective.

8.0.0.6 Fair P-Assignment

Fair P-Assignment is a reassignment method that reassigns points to different clusters based on a lambda-additive violation. This method can be used on lower-bounded clustering, for example, clustering bound by the fairness notion of bounded representation.

8.0.0.7 Deep Fair Clustering

This is a refinement learning algorithm that uses a LP solver to produce a fair, deep clustering. They do this by introducing an augmentation period after each clustering period along with an augmentation loss to be mitigated.

8.0.0.8 Decorrelation Regularized K-Means

This method introduces a correlation cost which is the sum of intra-cluster and inter-cluster costs to be minimized during the clustering process.

8.0.0.9 Representativity Fairness and K-Mean (RFKM)

This method introduces a novel fairness loss term for RFKM in order to optimize representativity fairness quantified by the representativity of protected classes within the dataset.

10 Data Analytics Methods

One of the goals for the clustering team is to implement several of the fairness notions and one of the bias mitigation algorithms as a demonstration of the use cases of the ontology. In order to tackle this goal, we implemented a few of the fairness notions we collected, (Balance, Entropy, Max Fairness Cost, Jung Et Al Individual Fairness Distance, Essential Fairness Maximum Proportion Difference, Per Point Fairness Violations, Aggregate Fairness Violations). Used the notions to evaluate the fairness of our bias mitigation technique , Fairlet Decomposition, by comparing the scores to baseline models (SciKit Learns implementation of K-Means and K-Medians Clustering).

Originally, the bias mitigation algorithm we wanted to implement was the fairlet decomposition algorithm proposed in Fair Clustering Through Fairlets. However, that paper lacked any official public repositories. We found another paper, Scalable Fair Clustering, that proposed a modification to the fairlet decomposition algorithm that claims to achieve similar results with a better time complexity. Since this paper did infact provide publically available code, we decided to go with this algorithm. The general idea of the fairlet decomposition algorithm is to seperate the dataset into very small (3-5 point clusters) which satisfy the balance notion. These tiny clusters are called fairlets. Afterwards, applying any general clustering algorithm on the fairlets should yield clusters which also satisfy the balance notion, and therefore be deemed fair. This is the general idea of the fairlet algorithm.

The repository for, Scalable Fair Clustering, could be found here: https://github.com/talwagner/fair_clustering

The following code chunk contains the code for fairlet decomposition which is copied directly from the official repo.

EPSILON = 0.0001
 
FAIRLETS = []
FAIRLET_CENTERS = []
 
class TreeNode:
 
    def __init__(self):
        self.children = []
 
    def set_cluster(self, cluster):
        self.cluster = cluster
 
    def add_child(self, child):
        self.children.append(child)
 
    def populate_colors(self, colors):
        "Populate auxiliary lists of red and blue points for each node, bottom-up"
        self.reds = []
        self.blues = []
        if len(self.children) == 0:
            # Leaf
            for i in self.cluster:
                if colors[i] == 0:
                    self.reds.append(i)
                else:
                    self.blues.append(i)
        else:
            # Not a leaf
            for child in self.children:
                child.populate_colors(colors)
                self.reds.extend(child.reds)
                self.blues.extend(child.blues)
 
 
### K-MEDIAN CODE ###
 
def kmedian_cost(points, centroids, dataset):
    "Computes and returns k-median cost for given dataset and centroids"
    return sum(np.amin(np.concatenate([np.linalg.norm(dataset[:,:]-dataset[centroid,:], axis=1).reshape((dataset.shape[0], 1)) for centroid in centroids], axis=1), axis=1))

def fair_kmedian_cost(centroids, dataset):
    "Return the fair k-median cost for given centroids and fairlet decomposition"
    total_cost = 0
    for i in range(len(FAIRLETS)):
        # Choose index of centroid which is closest to the i-th fairlet center
        cost_list = [np.linalg.norm(dataset[centroids[j],:]-dataset[FAIRLET_CENTERS[i],:]) for j in range(len(centroids))]
        cost, j = min((cost, j) for (j, cost) in enumerate(cost_list))
        # Assign all points in i-th fairlet to above centroid and compute cost
        total_cost += sum([np.linalg.norm(dataset[centroids[j],:]-dataset[point,:]) for point in FAIRLETS[i]])
    return total_cost
 
 
### FAIRLET DECOMPOSITION CODE ###
 
def balanced(p, q, r, b):
    if r==0 and b==0:
        return True
    if r==0 or b==0:
        return False
    return min(r*1./b, b*1./r) >= p*1./q
 
 
def make_fairlet(points, dataset):
    "Adds fairlet to fairlet decomposition, returns median cost"
    FAIRLETS.append(points)
    cost_list = [sum([np.linalg.norm(dataset[center,:]-dataset[point,:]) for point in points]) for center in points]
    cost, center = min((cost, center) for (center, cost) in enumerate(cost_list))
    FAIRLET_CENTERS.append(points[center])
    return cost
 
 
def basic_fairlet_decomposition(p, q, blues, reds, dataset):
    """
    Computes vanilla (p,q)-fairlet decomposition of given points (Lemma 3 in NIPS17 paper).
    Returns cost.
    Input: Balance parameters p,q which are non-negative integers satisfying p<=q and gcd(p,q)=1.
    "blues" and "reds" are sets of points indices with balance at least p/q.
    """
    assert p <= q, "Please use balance parameters in the correct order"
    if len(reds) < len(blues):
        temp = blues
        blues = reds
        reds = temp
    R = len(reds)
    B = len(blues)
    assert balanced(p, q, R, B), "Input sets are unbalanced: "+str(R)+","+str(B)
 
    if R==0 and B==0:
        return 0
 
    b0 = 0
    r0 = 0
    cost = 0
    while (R-r0)-(B-b0) >= q-p and R-r0 >= q and B-b0 >= p:
        cost += make_fairlet(reds[r0:r0+q]+blues[b0:b0+p], dataset)
        r0 += q
        b0 += p
    if R-r0 + B-b0 >=1 and R-r0 + B-b0 <= p+q:
        cost += make_fairlet(reds[r0:]+blues[b0:], dataset)
        r0 = R
        b0 = B
    elif R-r0 != B-b0 and B-b0 >= p:
        cost += make_fairlet(reds[r0:r0+(R-r0)-(B-b0)+p]+blues[b0:b0+p], dataset)
        r0 += (R-r0)-(B-b0)+p
        b0 += p
    assert R-r0 == B-b0, "Error in computing fairlet decomposition"
    for i in range(R-r0):
        cost += make_fairlet([reds[r0+i], blues[b0+i]], dataset)
    return cost
 
 
def node_fairlet_decomposition(p, q, node, dataset, donelist, depth):

    # Leaf                                                                                          
    if len(node.children) == 0:
        node.reds = [i for i in node.reds if donelist[i]==0]
        node.blues = [i for i in node.blues if donelist[i]==0]
        assert balanced(p, q, len(node.reds), len(node.blues)), "Reached unbalanced leaf"
        return basic_fairlet_decomposition(p, q, node.blues, node.reds, dataset)
 
    # Preprocess children nodes to get rid of points that have already been clustered
    for child in node.children:
        child.reds = [i for i in child.reds if donelist[i]==0]
        child.blues = [i for i in child.blues if donelist[i]==0]
 
    R = [len(child.reds) for child in node.children]
    B = [len(child.blues) for child in node.children]
 
    if sum(R) == 0 or sum(B) == 0:
        assert sum(R)==0 and sum(B)==0, "One color class became empty for this node while the other did not"
        return 0
 
    NR = 0
    NB = 0
 
    # Phase 1: Add must-remove nodes
    for i in range(len(node.children)):
        if R[i] >= B[i]:
            must_remove_red = max(0, R[i] - int(np.floor(B[i]*q*1./p)))
            R[i] -= must_remove_red
            NR += must_remove_red
        else:
            must_remove_blue = max(0, B[i] - int(np.floor(R[i]*q*1./p)))
            B[i] -= must_remove_blue
            NB += must_remove_blue
 
    # Calculate how many points need to be added to smaller class until balance
    if NR >= NB:
        # Number of missing blues in (NR,NB)
        missing = max(0, int(np.ceil(NR*p*1./q)) - NB)
    else:
        # Number of missing reds in (NR,NB)
        missing = max(0, int(np.ceil(NB*p*1./q)) - NR)
         
    # Phase 2: Add may-remove nodes until (NR,NB) is balanced or until no more such nodes
    for i in range(len(node.children)):
        if missing == 0:
            assert balanced(p, q, NR, NB), "Something went wrong"
            break
        if NR >= NB:
            may_remove_blue = B[i] - int(np.ceil(R[i]*p*1./q))
            remove_blue = min(may_remove_blue, missing)
            B[i] -= remove_blue
            NB += remove_blue
            missing -= remove_blue
        else:
            may_remove_red = R[i] - int(np.ceil(B[i]*p*1./q))
            remove_red = min(may_remove_red, missing)
            R[i] -= remove_red
            NR += remove_red
            missing -= remove_red
 
    # Phase 3: Add unsatuated fairlets until (NR,NB) is balanced
    for i in range(len(node.children)):
        if balanced(p, q, NR, NB):
            break
        if R[i] >= B[i]:
            num_saturated_fairlets = int(R[i]/q)
            excess_red = R[i] - q*num_saturated_fairlets
            excess_blue = B[i] - p*num_saturated_fairlets
        else:
            num_saturated_fairlets = int(B[i]/q)
            excess_red = R[i] - p*num_saturated_fairlets
            excess_blue = B[i] - q*num_saturated_fairlets
        R[i] -= excess_red
        NR += excess_red
        B[i] -= excess_blue
        NB += excess_blue
 
    assert balanced(p, q, NR, NB), "Constructed node sets are unbalanced"
 
    reds = []
    blues = []
    for i in range(len(node.children)):
        for j in node.children[i].reds[R[i]:]:
            reds.append(j)
            donelist[j] = 1
        for j in node.children[i].blues[B[i]:]:
            blues.append(j)
            donelist[j] = 1
 
    assert len(reds)==NR and len(blues)==NB, "Something went horribly wrong"
 
    return basic_fairlet_decomposition(p, q, blues, reds, dataset) + sum([node_fairlet_decomposition(p, q, child, dataset, donelist, depth+1) for child in node.children])
 
 
def tree_fairlet_decomposition(p, q, root, dataset, colors):
    "Main fairlet clustering function, returns cost wrt original metric (not tree metric)"
    assert p <= q, "Please use balance parameters in the correct order"
    root.populate_colors(colors)
    assert balanced(p, q, len(root.reds), len(root.blues)), "Dataset is unbalanced"
    root.populate_colors(colors)
    donelist = [0] * dataset.shape[0]
    return node_fairlet_decomposition(p, q, root, dataset, donelist, 0)
 
 
### QUADTREE CODE ###
 
def build_quadtree(dataset, max_levels=0, random_shift=True):
    "If max_levels=0 there no level limit, quadtree will partition until all clusters are singletons"
    dimension = dataset.shape[1]
    lower = np.amin(dataset, axis=0)
    upper = np.amax(dataset, axis=0)
 
    shift = np.zeros(dimension)
    if random_shift:
        for d in range(dimension):
            spread = upper[d] - lower[d]
            shift[d] = np.random.uniform(0, spread)
            upper[d] += spread
 
    return build_quadtree_aux(dataset, range(dataset.shape[0]), lower, upper, max_levels, shift)
     
 
def build_quadtree_aux(dataset, cluster, lower, upper, max_levels, shift):
    """
    "lower" is the "bottom-left" (in all dimensions) corner of current hypercube
    "upper" is the "upper-right" (in all dimensions) corner of current hypercube
    """
 
    dimension = dataset.shape[1]
    cell_too_small = True
    for i in range(dimension):
        if upper[i]-lower[i] > EPSILON:
            cell_too_small = False
 
    node = TreeNode()
    if max_levels==1 or len(cluster)<=1 or cell_too_small:
        # Leaf
        node.set_cluster(cluster)
        return node
     
    # Non-leaf
    midpoint = 0.5 * (lower + upper)
    subclusters = defaultdict(list)
    for i in cluster:
        subclusters[tuple([dataset[i,d]+shift[d]<=midpoint[d] for d in range(dimension)])].append(i)
    for edge, subcluster in subclusters.items():
        sub_lower = np.zeros(dimension)
        sub_upper = np.zeros(dimension)
        for d in range(dimension):
            if edge[d]:
                sub_lower[d] = lower[d]
                sub_upper[d] = midpoint[d]
            else:
                sub_lower[d] = midpoint[d]
                sub_upper[d] = upper[d]
        node.add_child(build_quadtree_aux(dataset, subcluster, sub_lower, sub_upper, max_levels-1, shift))
    return node

11 Evaluated Metrics:

The following are a list of notions whose metrics we have implemented and evaluated in our experiments.

11.0.0.1 Disparate Impact:

Balance: This code calculates the balance of a clustering algorithm. The balance is essentially the proportion of the number of label 0 for the protected attributes in a dataset over the number of label 1s. The goal for balance is to have the balance of the entire dataset be equal to the minimum balance for the clusters. For more than two classes of data, it is recommended to use Max Fairness Cost or Essential Fairness.

def balance(protected, clusters, num_clusters):
    a_entire = np.sum(protected==0)
    b_entire = np.sum(protected!=0)
    bal_arr = np.zeros(num_clusters)
    for i in range(num_clusters):
        c = protected[clusters==i]
        a = np.sum(c==0)
        b = np.sum(c!=0)
        bal_arr[i] = min(a/b, b/a)
    return np.min(bal_arr), min(a_entire/b_entire, b_entire/a_entire), bal_arr

11.0.0.2 Relaxed Disparate Impact:

Max Fairness Cost: The max fairness cost is the maximum of the difference between the proprotion of protected attributs in a cluster and the ideal proportion. The goal is to minimize the max fairness cost as a high max fairness cost is less fair.

def max_fairness_cost(protected, clusters, num_clusters, ideal_proportion):
    cost_arr = np.zeros(num_clusters)
    for i in range(num_clusters):
        c = protected[clusters==i]
        a = np.sum(c==0)
        b = np.sum(c!=0)
        cost_arr[i] = np.abs(min(a/b, b/a) - ideal_proportion)
    return np.max(cost_arr), cost_arr

11.0.0.3 Essential Fairness:

A clustering is fair if the ratio of all protected classes is preserved in each cluster. A relaxed version of this metric allows for the ratio of all protected classes to be preserved within a certain error.

def essential_fairness(protected, clusters, num_clusters):
    '''
    Calculates the difference in proportion for a protected class
    in the original dataset versus the proportion in each cluster.
    Returns the maximum difference.
    '''
    diffs = np.zeros(num_clusters)
    for i in range(num_clusters):
        c = protected[clusters==i]
        cluster_prot = np.sum(c==0)/c.shape[0]
        dataset_prot = np.sum(protected==0)/protected.shape[0]
        diffs[i] = cluster_prot-dataset_prot
    return np.max(diffs), diffs

11.0.0.4 Independence (Statistical Parity)

Entropy: Entropy is the measure of how well distributed the protected attribute is in the dataset. The lower the entropy value, the less distributed. The higher the entropy, the more distributed the protected attribute is. Therefore, a higher entropy value is more fair.

def entropy(dataset, protected, clusters, num_clusters):
    e = 0
    for i in range(num_clusters):
        c = protected[clusters==i]
        c_dataset = dataset[clusters==i]
        c_protected = c_dataset[np.tile((c==0).reshape(-1,1), (1,c_dataset.shape[1]))].reshape(-1, c_dataset.shape[1])
        next_e = (np.linalg.norm(c_protected)/c.shape[0]) * np.log(np.linalg.norm(c_protected)/c.shape[0])
        if (not np.isnan(next_e)):
            e += next_e
    return -e

11.0.0.5 Load Balance

Jung et al Individual Fairness: A clustering is fair if each point finds a center within its neighborhood radius. This fairness accounts for population density. The goal is to minimize maximum travel distance in k-center, average travel distance in k-median, and the sum of squares of travel distances in k-means.

def jung_fairness(dataset, clusters, num_clusters, centers, method="median"):
    '''
    Evaluates jung et al fairness and returns the maximum average
    travel distance in k-median, sum of squares of travel distances in
    k-means, and the maximum travel distance in k-center.
    Distance calculation is normalized
    '''
    objs = np.zeros(num_clusters)
    for i in range(num_clusters):
        c = dataset[clusters==i]
        dists = np.linalg.norm(c - centers[i], axis=1)
        if method == "median":
            objs[i] = np.mean(dists)
        elif method == "mean":
            objs[i] = np.sum(np.square(dists))
        else:
            objs[i] = np.max(dists)
        
    return max(objs), objs

11.0.0.6 Individual Fairness

Per Point Fairness: For any point, the distance from it to the cluster center must be less than alpha times the distance from the cluster center to the closest point.

Aggregate Fairness: For any point, the distance from it to the cluster center must be less than alpha times the average distance from the cluster center to a point in the cluster.

def pp_agg_fairness(dataset, clusters, num_clusters, centers, alpha = 6, agg=False):
    '''
    Calculates either per point or aggregate fairness metric,
    returns the maximum violations in a cluster and violations
    per cluster.
    Distance calculation is normalized
    '''
    violations = np.zeros(num_clusters)
    for i in range(num_clusters):
        c = dataset[clusters==i]
        dists = np.linalg.norm(c - centers[i], axis=1)
        if agg:
            obj = alpha * np.mean(dists)
        else:
            obj = alpha * np.min(dists)
        diffs = dists - obj
        violations[i] = np.sum(diffs>0)/diffs.shape[0]
    return np.max(violations), violations

12 Ideal Cluster Size

Our inital number of clusters was selected to be 20 because that is what is used in the Fair Clustering With Fairlets paper. However, when running the code on the datasets, it is quicky apparent that 20 clusters is way too high. In order to find the optimal number of clusters, an elbow plot is used. Below is code which will calculate the optimal number of clusters for both sklearn’s k-means and k-medians clustering algorithm using an elbow plot.

num_points = 10000

datasets = [bank_dataset[:num_points], adult_dataset[:num_points]]
K = range(1,21)
for i, X in enumerate(datasets):
    distortions = []
    inertias = []
    mapping1 = {}
    mapping2 = {}
    for k in K:
        kmeanModel = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=0).fit(X)
        kmeanModel.fit(X)
    
        distortions.append(sum(np.min(cdist(X, kmeanModel.cluster_centers_,
                                            'euclidean'), axis=1)) / X.shape[0])
        inertias.append(kmeanModel.inertia_)
    
        mapping1[k] = sum(np.min(cdist(X, kmeanModel.cluster_centers_,
                                    'euclidean'), axis=1)) / X.shape[0]
        mapping2[k] = kmeanModel.inertia_
    plt.plot(K, distortions, 'bx-')
    plt.xlabel('Values of K')
    plt.xticks(K)
    plt.ylabel('Distortion')
    plt.title(f'Elbow Plot for Kmeans Clustering on {"Bank" if i == 0 else "Adult"} datset')
    plt.show()

for i, X in enumerate(datasets):
    distortions = []
    inertias = []
    mapping1 = {}
    mapping2 = {}
    for k in K:
        kmedianModel = KMedoids(n_clusters=k, random_state=0).fit(X)
        kmedianModel.fit(X)
    
        distortions.append(sum(np.min(cdist(X, kmedianModel.cluster_centers_,
                                            'euclidean'), axis=1)) / X.shape[0])
        inertias.append(kmedianModel.inertia_)
    
        mapping1[k] = sum(np.min(cdist(X, kmedianModel.cluster_centers_,
                                    'euclidean'), axis=1)) / X.shape[0]
        mapping2[k] = kmedianModel.inertia_
    plt.plot(K, distortions, 'bx-')
    plt.xticks(K)
    plt.xlabel('Values of K')
    plt.ylabel('Distortion')
    plt.title(f'Elbow Plot for Kmedian Clustering on {"Bank" if i == 0 else "Adult"} datset')
    plt.show()

fairlet_clusters = np.zeros(dataset.shape[0])
for i in range(len(FAIRLET_CENTERS)):
    for j in range(len(FAIRLETS)):
        if(FAIRLET_CENTERS[i] in FAIRLETS[j]):
            for k in range(len(FAIRLETS[j])):
                fairlet_clusters[FAIRLETS[j][k]] = kmedoids.labels_[i]

bal, bal_dataset, bal_arr = balance(adult_protected[:num_points], fairlet_clusters, 9)
print(f"Minimum Cluster Balance: {bal:.4f}")
## Minimum Cluster Balance: 0.5000
print(f"Balance of Entire Dataset: {bal_dataset:.4f}")
## Balance of Entire Dataset: 0.5008
ent = entropy(adult_dataset[:num_points], adult_protected[:num_points], fairlet_clusters, 9)
print(f"Entropy of Clusters: {ent:.4f}")
## Entropy of Clusters: 0.0153
mfc, mfc_arr = max_fairness_cost(adult_protected[:num_points], fairlet_clusters, 9, bal_dataset)
print(f"Max Fairness Cost: {mfc:.4f}")
## Max Fairness Cost: 0.0027
jung, jung_arr = jung_fairness(adult_dataset[:num_points, 1:], fairlet_clusters, 9, kmedoids.cluster_centers_)
print(f"Jung Et Al Individual Fairness Distance: {jung:.4f}")
## Jung Et Al Individual Fairness Distance: 0.0042
essential, essential_arr = essential_fairness(adult_protected[:num_points], fairlet_clusters, 9)
print(f"Essential Fairness Maximum Proportion Difference: {essential:.4f}")
## Essential Fairness Maximum Proportion Difference: 0.0012
pp, pp_arr = pp_agg_fairness(adult_dataset[:num_points, 1:], fairlet_clusters, 9, kmedoids.cluster_centers_)
print(f"Per Point Fairness Violations: {pp:.4f}")
## Per Point Fairness Violations: 0.9993
agg, agg_arr = pp_agg_fairness(adult_dataset[:num_points, 1:], fairlet_clusters, 9, kmedoids.cluster_centers_, agg = True)
print(f"Aggregate Fairness Violations: {agg:.4f}")
## Aggregate Fairness Violations: 0.0111

The results of running the two baseline algorithms and the bias mitigation algorithn, we found that the bias mitigation algorithm was most effective in improving the balance of the dataset. On the table, we can see that the two baseline models have a balance much lower than the balance of the entire dataset, while the Fairlet Decomposition algorithm has a balance which is almost the same as the balance of the entire dataset. This means that the proportion of the protected attribute in each cluster is very close to the proportion of the protected attribute in the entire dataset, which shows that each cluster represents the protected attribute the same way the protected attribute is represented in the entire dataset. For evaluating the Max-Fairness Cost, I set the ideal proportion to be equal to the balance of the dataset because I wanted the ideal proportion of the protected attribute in each cluster to be equal to the proportion of the protected attribute in the entire dataset. Therefore, the results from balance should be correlated to the values from the Max-Fairness Cost. As expected, the Fairlet Decomposition performed way better than the baseline model since the Fairlet Decomposition algorithm’s balance values were much closer to the balance of the entire dataset than the Baseline models. For Essential Fairness Proportional deviation, we expect the Fairlet Decomposition algorithm to perform the best because it is another proportion based fairness notion. Note, the lower the Essential Fairness Proportional Deviation is, the more fair a clustering algorithm is. As expected, this is the case. The results from Essential Fairness Proportional Deviation were directly correlated with Max Fairness Cost, with the Fairlet Decomposition algorithm blowing the baseline models out of the water. Unfortunately, we found that the Fairlet Decomposition algorithm did not show significant increase in fairness for the other fairness notions. On the tables, we can see that the values for Entropy, Per Point Violations, and Aggregate Violations (which are based on distance) for the Baseline K-medians clustering algorithm, and Fairlet Decomposition algorithm are quite similar. We believe this is the case because the Fairlet Decomposition algorithm is a preprocessing algorithm that converts the dataset into fairlets before it is clustered. The cluster the fairlets is done by the same clustering algorithm as the baseline k-medians clustering algorithm. Since the goal of the fairlet decomposition algorithm is the reduce proportion based bias, it would make sense that for other notions of fairness to not be reduced by this algorithm. From our analysis, we conclude that the Fairlet Decomposition algorithm is a good bias mitigation algorithm for proportion based fairness.

15 Conclusions

From the results of our research, we can conclude that most clustering algorithms are not inherently fair, and to address this, it is important to consider the use of fairness notions and metrics to not only learn in what way a clustering is unfair through fairness metrics, but also how to address these biases through bias mitigation. From the outstanding results of the bias mitigation method that we evaluated on K-Medians: Fairlet Decomposition, we have seen the effectiveness and benefits of applying a mitigation algorithm on the fairness of clustering results. Applying Fairlet Decomposition has resulted in the improvement of all the metrics we evaluated in this paper, despite most of them not even being related to disparate impact or balance. Hence, we recommend that individuals and even large corportations take the time to look into what the field of fairness has for their clustering solutions and how they can leverage these methods to improve the effectiveness of their clustering models. We strongly believe that any company can find a use in our results, even profit-based companies whose main goal is to earn money through successful marketing who may not consider fairness as important may come to see that there are points where fairness will not only not hinder their profits, but even drastically improve them.

16 Directions for Future Investigation

Possible future extensions to our research may include the development of new fairness notions, metrics, or mitigation methods and the creation of an R (or Python) package that will make these metrics and mitigation methods accessible to all users who may be concerned with fairness in their clustering algorithms without having the necessary knowledge. Through our research, we have discovered a lack of novel notions, metrics, and mitigation methods. We believe that our research will provide a good foundation and reference material for any researcher looking to gather inspiration on developing their own fairness metrics to be tested on datasets with protected groups. We also believe that a package enabling laymen to apply fairness metrics in their own clustering pursuits will allow the concept of fairness to permeate the field of clustering and machine learning in general by making fairness accessible to all.
